<br>
1. I have similar doubts about the bidding system for the reasons mentioned already. Give loot a fixed 'price' and random if several people want it - that way, points still do matter and we avoid fluctuations in 'point costs' (see above).<br>
<br>
2. Make the point system as simple as possible and as complex as necessary. I know, I sound like a politician here, so let me elaborate. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  The current system appears to be rather 'complex' to me, in terms of following it on a raid. Things are often busy enough with organizing loot roles while fighting ... imagine you would have to keep track of a rather complicated point distribution system at the same time. So I agree with you, Mori, that we should not reallocate points everytime SCARAB is up to something. If I can, I will help a SCARAB member to do what he/she wants to do, regardless of points that I might get from it. After all, this is also supposed to grow into a community (a 'guildlike' organization) where you help the friends you made. &quot;'tis not all about the money (read: points)&quot; ... <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  There should be something like points, however, to avoid people coming in just to get help and do nothing in return. So again, I prefer a rather simple system (that does not cover all possible constellations) that does not distract from playing and the 'community' idea ... <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Take care,<br>
<br>
Karolusx/Etidure<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/bscarab5467.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=llador>Llador</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 7<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(10/16/02 12:09)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub10.ezboard.com/fscarab5467frm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=26.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: new points system: bidding!</span><hr size=1> If it aint broke don't fix it <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <br>
<br>
Has there been problems (ie complaints) about the current system?  The only (minor) one I have is that it's going to take some time to get rid my negative points based on my availability and the raid/fight rate atm. That is something I knew before joined up, just as I knew the system that is in place to get loot. A good loot system is a difficult one to set up and manage but I think the current one appears about as fair as you can get and gives everyone a chance. <br>
<br>
You mention setting a fixed number of points for a piece of loot and of players giving out points for help on raids. From what I see that's the system we have anyway. Changing it to a bidding system pushes the scales in favour of those who are fortunate to attend more raids. Whilst it is true that those people should be rewarded the current roll system should, by the law of averages, work favourably for those players anyway. A bidding system might cost membership - especially if players are limited to the times they can join in.<br>
<br>
One other consideration (sorry for the long post but I think it is important). What about mercenary recruitment? I have just had another look at the rules (Points System). <br>
<br>
Quote:<br>
A ranger needs help with the EK epic fight, so he recruits 2 full groups (minus himself) from SCARAB, the fight rewards everyone present with 1 point, however, since the only loot is in fact for the ranger himself, he must GIVE HIS/HER points to the group recruited. ie: if you recruit 11 SCARAB members to help you with a fight, you are required to pay the 11 points out from your own point pool in order to do this raid/fight. However, you must also pay for the loot claimed out of your own points pool as well, so in the end, for recruition of 11 SCARAB's, you will make a net loss of 11 points plus a few points depending on what quest item(s) were looted (which can be easily made back...but recruit wisely...you are of course able to recruit a mix of friends and SCARABs...think of SCARAB as a mercenary guild when recruiting for your own purposes: they want to be paid). Most quest items in this case will be 1-2 points. If a mob drops multiple copies of the same quest item and multiple people are present who wish to loot them, they must split the points pay-out to the recruited group, and each pay the point cost of the quest item looted.<br>
<br>
In addition, if there is dropped loot, the point value of this loot can be deducted from the points that the recruiting person needs to pay out, assuming of course that the loot is claimed by someone present instead of points (ie: if you also get an item worth 1 point which someone wants to claim instead of his/her point, you can award them this item instead of giving them your points. Another example: if an item worth 10 points is looted, someone can forfeit their 1 point plus 9 extra points from their points pool to claim it, and you will not have to pay their 1 point for the fight. All loot from these fights is claimed by the person paying out the points.)<br>
(end quote)<br>
<br>
How will this be handled? Having players bid may mean the recruiting player may pay very heavily if the bidding is fierce. If we are saying just a fixed number of points is deducted then this makes it unfair to those that have had to bid for the item on previous occasions.<br>
<br>
<br>
I agree that there is always room for improvement but as I said at the beginning, if it aint broke, dont fix it  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <br>
 <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/bscarab5467.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=llador>Llador</A> at: 10/16/02 12:28:11 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/umoriminomoto.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Mori Minomoto</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Drunken Master</span><br>  Posts: 108<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(10/16/02 22:46)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub10.ezboard.com/fscarab5467frm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=26.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: new points system: bidding!</span><hr size=1> if you want a summarized version of this ranting i continually tend to do, skip to the bottom where i've decided to write up a short scorecard ;)<br>
i type too damn much.......nothing i can do about it......sorry ;)<br>
<br>
well first i must give a huge thank you to all the feedback, some very interesting and valuable points made all across......<br>
<br>
i just wanted to clear up some misconceptions and/or things that werent clear, possibly, with the original system that have thus led to alot of unwarranted negative thoughts about this bidding system proposal.......<br>
<br>
<br>
ambrielle first:<br>
-point about the phinny drop.  right, so theres more then 1 wiz or druid there to fight over it...however, even with our current system, in a phinny type hit, it is most likely someone who organized it that wants the drop, and regardless of points, the person organizing it will get it.......in this type of thing, the person organizing will use our still-yet-to-be-used 'mercenary' type 'recruiting' to get the members he/she needs for the hit to be made.......(ideally we would all just go help and etc but paying someone a point to come help was an idea i had that could just expand on the uses of scarab points).....<br>
-the problem with fixed loot point values is simple, and we have already encountered this problem a few times...that problem is quite simply that it is impossible to go and pre-assign point values to all the loot in the game......i mean cmon, of the 50k+ items that exist in the game, at least 10% of that would be loot we would possibly encounter and roll for, lets say, but that still leaves a huge number of items to go and set pricetags on......and who gets to say what those prices are?  also, as we have already seen, price tagging items is ultimately unfair, in the strictist sense, because we dont always know the rarity, the rarity may change, the value of the item itself may change, and i could go on about hundreds of different factors as to why setting a fixed value on something is in fact quite bad........(nothing in EQ has a fixed price, so trying to set a fixed price in points is sortof futile......a brood axe 6 months ago sold for 10k.......if one dropped today is someone still going to pay 10 points for it? doubtful, in fact, impossible.....)<br>
this forecasting of mine is primarily why i dont like my own system.......originally i had intended it to be a loose system that could change from raid to raid, but as we started getting some complaints about 'oh but he only paid 2 points for that last raid why do i have to pay 3?' (or vice versa) the quickest solution was to just say "ok, fixed points, sorry".......i should have thought more thoroughly and not said that but i did so whats done is done......<br>
<br>
iilea, you also made the same point as ambrielle did about items not having the same prices in a bidding system at different times....this i have addressed above, in the fact that our points system was originally intended to be the exact same way........base item prices based on what they currently selling for in bazaar (average of all prices or something fair thereabouts) was what the system was intended to do, so prices were never intended to be fixed, and if you agree with my point above about the brood axe ;) you will also thereby agree that prices should in fact NOT be fixed......<br>
being there at the right time is always going to be a factor in EQ......i know that now for damn sure after camping this bloody white chicken stormfeather for over 45 hours since sunday........however this factor, in a 'fair' system, *should* be minimized......<br>
<br>
so i propose an addition to the bidding system:<br>
<br>
the thing i want to propose to fix the issue about someone bidding all their points on phinny drop or some such versus someone bidding only the minimum points because they are the only one there for the class is that we could assign point values to items based on rarity......<br>
now comparing phinny to fist of fire isnt exactly a comparison ;) fist of fire can be auto-spawned every 15 minutes and phinny can take a week to spawn in the bottom of a zone only truly accessable with a good invis and EB item......<br>
assigning points to an item based on rarity, we could assign them on a range of 1 to 6 points......that is, 6 points would be *the* uber item in *the* uber zone that alot of ppl are going to want to bid on......now the thing that will hopefully fix the "he paid 10 points for his and i only paid 1 for mine" is that the MAXIMUM amount of points one would be allowed to bid on an item, is its 'rarity' value times 2.......thus, if an item dropped with a rarity value of 6 (the highest), you could bid 12 points on it maximum, and sure, even if there are multiple ppl bidding max points, it can still be resolved via the ML rolling.....this would mean that, say, some chain quest pants or boots or whatever dropped in kael and 3 ppl want it, for examples sake lets say it has a rarity value of 2, so they could all bid up to 4 points.......now, lets say theres only 1 person who is chain class present (not likely, but lets just say), he/she obviously wants to bid lowest and get em cheap - ie 2 points - is that such a big threat to the person who paid 4 points during the last raid? personally, ill say this now, i dont give a damn if im on every raid that is full of monks (or whatever im playing) which cause me to pay double in this kind of a system every single time.....thats fine with me, because ill eventually get some of the neat gear i want and if i have to help out twice as much as some other monk to get it then so be it, things are actually alot worse for me now anyway ;)<br>
<br>
im rambling now i know but i hope i made some points clear.....<br>
the system we have *is* in a sense broken, it just hasnt broken yet ;) but i can pretty much predict that it will, and will cause alot of unhappiness and i want to avoid that.....im good at predicting the future in this way, dont believe me if you dont want to but if you know me at all you will, because ive proven it to you sometime or another ;)<br>
<br>
i also reviewed another system that another guild uses which is quite simple and, as far as my inquiries, works quite OK:<br>
you get 1, 2 or 3 points per raid based on a predetermined 'size' and 'time' the raid requires, you then claim loot by resetting your raid points back to 0......which basically means you can only get 1 piece of loot per raid because you cant claim a second piece after already setting points to 0 ;) in the case that "nobody else" is around to loot something that "obviously" you are going to get most use out of, yet you have already looted something, and (for this example) lets say they are both ND items, you can then forfiet your next raids points for it.....<br>
now when claiming loot this way, the highest points gets first dibs, so the person that hasnt gotten loot for awhile will end up getting the item he/she wants......but the flip side to this is that, as some of the above posts have said is bad, that 'timing is everything'.....what if youre the lucky guy that goes on a raid time and time again only having points from your previous raid and continually claiming loot because nobody else of your class is around?<br>
<br>
to that i have but one thing to say: well in that case youre a lucky one and no points system in the world is going to stop you ;) and in all reality, thats just the way it is.......and personally, as ive already said, i dont give a damn and i am in fact quite happy for someone else who gets something more easily then me ;) im not a person that groans when someone else gets a loot item i want, im a person that claps and says 'whoa wtg man thats awesome!' and i have a big grin on my face thats just as big as it would be if i were the one to get it......hrmmm, maybe im wierd? too bad if i am, because then the rest of ye can goto hell ;)<br>
<br>
(and for those who dont know me, i have a sick sense of humor where i like to make fun of our stupid humanly downfalls......so dont take anything too seriously.....words to live by ;)<br>
<br>
SUMMARY:<br>
<br>
complaints of bidding system:<br>
-loots wont have 'fixed' point values, due to "being at the right raid at the right time" problem<br>
-a few think our current sysytem is not broken so why change it ;)<br>
<br>
my answers:<br>
-giving loots all a rarity value between 1 and 6, or whatever, and then having the MAXIMUM allowed points payable for claiming something be the rarity value (1 through 6) times 2...any discrepencies thereof being rolled over<br>
-it would then be RAIDS which would have fixed point values...each would be given points roughly according to the time/size of groups required to do the raid.....<br>
-our current system if in fact quite flawed and doomed to fail because of 2 things: we CANT keep fixed point values on items because prices and value of items in EQ change daily, and because we also CANT go and pre-assign point values to 50,000 game items.......<br>
<br>
another totally different system would be to have a system, briefly explained, where:<br>
-points would be awarded, for example 1/2/3 points for each raid based on the raids time/size required<br>
-to claim loot you would reset your points to 0, thus in this kind of system, the more effort you put forward means the more possibility you have of getting that *uber drop* when it drops because youll have more points then anyone else wanting to claim it......that is, the person with highest points gets the loot, rolling randomly between discrepencies.....you would not bid in this system, and this system has a much higher chance of people paying wildly different amounts of points for the same item (due to the 'being at the right place at the right time factor') but in all honesty it is 100% fair because it is up to the person whether he/she wants to raid places just to stockpile points, or claim loot......either of which will ultimately reward the player...<br>
-in this system all of us will be reset to 0 points, and given points based on who HASNT looted from the raids already done by scarab......this would also happen with the bidding system<br>
-in order to request help for a quest hit or whatnot, the people attending the raid/group/etc for the mob hit will get points according to the same rules that regular raids get, yet it will be first dibs for the organizing person to loot the quest drop thus resetting his/her points.....this is a much less complex and a very smooth way to request help with quest stuff and will no doubt encourage everyone to setup raids to do their quest stuff (which is what we want, no?).....in short: the attendees will get easy points by helping another member with a quest, and the person doing the quest will get his/her drop<br>
<br>
<br>
ok maybe that wasnt so summarized ;) <p><HR>
