<br>
Ultimately the fairest loot system is that suggested above where once you loot something it resets your points to date back to zero. If you dont loot then you get points (set by pre-determined rules).<br>
<br>
This loot system works well where all the players have a fairly good level of equipment already. It kind of works less well when a new player with not so good equipment joins. In this instance they pick up more kit quickly, the balance being that they need it more. The really good stuff still goes to the players with better kit (as they have more points through not spending it). As long as people who agree to this system are aware of this then no problems I guess.<br>
<br>
Another question to ask of this loot system is the ability to loot anything. So if a really nice Paladin item drops (and it is NOT nodrop) and you are on the raid as your Enchanter do you still get the ability to request the loot. My answer to this is yes as Scarab is about rewarding the effort put in by the player and not the character. So if we apply this system then we are not applying the NBG way of doing things, lets just be clear about this.<br>
<br>
Multiple claims. If 2 items drop in a raid and you are the only person to want both can you get them, answer is yes. The first claim takes you back to zero pts. The second takes the pts from your next raid.<br>
<br>
Unclaimed loot. My opinion on unclaimed loot is that anyone in the raid should have 2 days from the end of the raid to make a request for the loot. To be eligible they must have had positive points at the end of the raid in which the item drops (no building up points on the next raid and then claiming it). After this point the item becomes open for anyone else to claim (within the next 7 days). At the end of the 7 day period the person who wants it with the highest points gets it (and their pts reset to zero). After this the item either gets sold (mony to Scarab funds) or remains open for claim (first person to claim gets it). <br>
<br>
How to apply this to the 'mercenary' raid. Hmmmm<br>
<br>
I guess you could apply some of the same rules, the person organising the raid gives up points to all the people hired to help. They are either reset to zero or possibly allowed to go negative (to a preset level). If anyone on the raid selects any other loot then the raid organiser does not need to give them anything (maybe bringing them less negative but never above zero), and the person who loots points is set to zero again.<br>
<br>
E.g. Person A has 10 points and organises a raid to get object Z. He recruits 7 people to help at a cost of 2 pts each. If only he loots on the raid then he gets a points total of -4 at the end (and has to do the next couple of raids with no chance of loot). If, however, 3 players loot other items on his raid then his end total is reset to 0 (10 minus 8 is above 0 and therefore reset to 0). The 3 players who looted get reset to 0, the remaining 4 players get the 2pts each added to their totals.<br>
<br>
Sorry to be long winded but had a lot to say :P <p><A HREF="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=186665">Thug - 60 War</A>
