</CENTER></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/uboldir.showPublicProfile?language=EN>boldir</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 4<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(10/21/02 12:46)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub10.ezboard.com/fscarab5467frm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=26.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> raid point systems</span><hr size=1> Hi,<br>
I've been looking at a range of raid point systems for a while, some are really complex e.g. where specific items have values and they need to keep a database of all the items and points etc.  Others are less complicated, e.g. get 1 point per raid, when you chose an item you lose all the points.<br>
<br>
From what I can gather the system needs to meet the following objectives: - <br>
<br>
1. Fair and recognises Effort.<br>
The system has to be fair so that people feel comfortable attending raids by knowing that the effort / reward ratio is balanced.<br>
<br>
2. Easy to manage.<br>
The system has to be as simple as possible so it's easy to manage and keep upto date.  The correct reporting channels for SCARAB raids needs to be set-up and maintained.<br>
<br>
3. Flexible<br>
The system has to be flexible enough to be applicable from the small epic encounter to the large dungeon crawl.<br>
<br>
With these objectives in mind there are a number of key rules which should be static no matter what form of point system is applied.<br>
<br>
1. Whenever an item (drop or no drop) is looted by guild member (main or alt), points are deducted.<br>
<br>
2. The system is Need Before Greed (NBG).  For example if CoF drops from Naggy, Uber_Wiz with 50 points cannot bid for the item unless there is no class available who wants the item.<br>
<br>
3. Items that go unclaimed can be looted by the guild banker and buyers can spend points at a later date on said items.<br>
<br>
Again with these criteria in place there are a number of other factors that go into making a fair raid.  I would suggest that we should assume that every player attending a raid should reasonably expect to be able to loot one item each.  This needs a little explaining.  Basically if Player_A goes on a raid he can fall into one of three criteria: <br>
<br>
1. He doesn't loot anything.  Therefore he should be credited with points for the next raid.<br>
2. He loots one item.  His point credit should be only changed (marginally), unchanged if he loots an average value item (I'll get on to this later).<br>
3.  He loots more than one item.  His point credit should be lowered. (if he loots average items)<br>
<br>
The point system I would propose is as follows: -<br>
<br>
2 Points for being at the raid from start to end.<br>
1 Point for arriving late or leaving early.<br>
1 Additional point per hour for anything over 3 hours.<br>
<br>
It is the job of the raid leader to keep track of point gains or his appointed deputy.<br>
<br>
The cost of items can fall into 4 categories, it is the job of the Master Looter (ML) / RL to decide on the value of the item.<br>
<br>
1 point - An item that provides marginal improvement and can be upgraded relatively easily. e.g. Plane class gloves or boots.<br>
<br>
2 points - An item that provides an improvement to the class and may be recognised for its ability in certain situations.  e.g. Plane class BP, Legs; Kael Quest Gloves, Boots etc.<br>
<br>
4 points - An item that provides a significant improvement to the class and is recognised as standard equipment for a level 55 - 60 character. e.g. HoT Quest BP, Legs.  Kael Quests BP, Legs etc.<br>
<br>
8 points - An item that is a class defining piece of equipment that is recognised as an excellent piece of equipment for level 55-60.  e.g. CoF, Mosquito Leg Earring, basically anything that is worth 50Kpp upwards.<br>
<br>
When an item drops the ML will announce the item link and point cost in the raid channel.  All those interested who are of the correct class and the correct number of points will send tells to the ML.  The person with the highest point credit will be awarded the item.  The point rating for the item will be deducted from the persons points.  In the event that no person has enough points, the person with the highest number of points claiming the item will be allowed to go into negative points.  However, once in negative points they will not be able to claim an item.<br>
<br>
If we assume that an initiate (like me) should attend 3 raids to assertain their quality, they should be started on -6 points.  Therefore once they have attended 3 raids on time and stayed all the way through they will then start to accumulate positive credit.<br>
<br>
An epic encounter should be treated as a 2-4 point item depending on the nature of the encounter, i.e. the time to complete.  Those attending should be credited 2 points.  (To encourage completion of epics).<br>
<br>
Hope this is useful,<br>
Cheers,<br>
Deslok.<br>
