[/quote]<br>
<br>
i couldnt agree with you more, but this is pretty obvious ;)<br>
you forgot one thing though<br>
4. a system that is unabusable<br>
that is, a system that cannot be abused by 'farming points', getting items for less, getting more privelages then earned, etc.<br>
<br>
[quote]<br>
1. Whenever an item (drop or no drop) is looted by guild member (main or alt), points are deducted.<br>
<br>
2. The system is Need Before Greed (NBG). For example if CoF drops from Naggy, Uber_Wiz with 50 points cannot bid for the item unless there is no class available who wants the item.<br>
<br>
3. Items that go unclaimed can be looted by the guild banker and buyers can spend points at a later date on said items.<br>
[/quote]<br>
<br>
once again, couldnt agree with you more, this is what we've been striving for in all the points systems we've been testing/discussing........it is however very nice that you summed up what needs to be done, so that we dont loose track, and dont sway off course...i think in our discussions of points systems, we have lost track of what the ultimate goal is......your post will be an immense help on 'putting us straight' again......however.......<br>
you then go on to explain a system, that is not simple, quite complex, and breaks our rule #1 when we are trying to put together a valid points system:<br>
<br>
rule #1: we cannot have point values for items, in anyway shape or form...value of items in EQ changes, and thus must the points deducted for an item when claimed be variant...before kunark, according to your system, a PoH/PoF piece of armor would cost 8 points, without argument...it was simply the uberest stuff in the game (armor? that gives STATS???? youre kidding me!!!).  i wouldnt pay more then a point, and in most cases not even that for old-world planes armor now. thus, simply put, we cannot apply any scarab points in any shape or form, to EQ items...it wont work<br>
<br>
your system also breaks your own rules on keeping things simple, not completely, but it still does.......it does this by introducing situation-dependant variables, and in the case that RL/ML decides what an item is worth in points, it also introduces a huge complexity called human oppinion ;)<br>
<br>
your system also breaks rule #2 for our 'points system creation excercise':<br>
rule #2: we cannot allow to reward more points, especially in a point-per-item-value deduction system, then we gain loot...if we reward more points then we have loot to claim, everyone will rack up tons of extra points, and they wont mean anything...it will be the ultimate form of inflation...very easy to make points, nothing to spend em on.....<br>
<br>
your system is concise and in principle simple, but suffice to say, it 'just wont work', not the way you want it to anyway ;)<br>
<br>
the only way a system will work, i say again, is if it ties no relation to WHICH item is looted.....that is, the amount of points deducted for looting an item, is independant from which item it is.....the point wipe system, imo, does this the best, and is also the best way to allow our previous 'mercenary recruitment' idea about scarab completely seamlessly......the bidding system takes care of all the above issues the same as the point wipe system, however, recruiting help from scarab's to help you when you need it, would require another add-on system just for that...because bidding for your reserved epic item isnt exactly feasible...youre always going to bid 1, and sure we can put some limitations in place, but then we are drifting towards breaking our rule #1 which states, clearly, that we cannot place point restrictions/values on eq item values.....<br>
<br>
<br>
i think the best system we are going to get, and in fact the most simple one, is the point wipe system......implemented simply first, and we can tweak it along the way (ie:how we reward points based on what zones are raided/time invested etc)<br>
<br>
<br>
--------POINT WIPE SYSTEM------------<br>
1)attending a raid gets you 1 point, coming on time, and staying through the entire thing, gets you another 1 point.  those that leave, go LD, come late, or leave early will only recieve their 1 point if the RL says they do.....this will hopefully disallow any abuse of ppl running from raid to raid, staying 5 minutes, getting their point, and leaving.....we can also thus say, that if you are on a raid, you are not allowed to get points for any other raid if it overlaps with the raid you are trying to get points on (ie: we have 2 planes raids, at the same time, or overlapping eachother in some way...you can only get points, regardless if you attend both partially, for 1 of the raids)<br>
<br>
2)to claim loot, you must have positive points, from previous raids (not the current one), and be willing to erase all of those points to zero in order to claim the loot item.....if you have over 10 points, looting an item will cost you a flat out 10....ive thought of having a variant system, that divides your points in half, or takes a percentage, etc. but it will not work in all situations.....if you are unfortunate enough to have been on many many raids and yet never had the chance to loot something you want, and have thus racked up a good deal of points, looting your next item or two might cost you alot (ie: 10 points) but it wont wipe you to 0.......it will also allow you to loot multiple items on the same raid, as long as you have positive points......10 points is equivalent, in most situations, to 4 or 5 raids.......so its not that whole heck of alot of points ;) i hope this sytem wont be too 'rewarding' and thus break our rule #2, but lets try it and find out i always say :)<br>
<br>
3)this is really part of #2, but will make another rule merely to clarify HOW looting works:<br>
first of all, when something is looted, it is NBG.....ideally only the classes who can use the item can claim it.....in the case of all/all items or items (like a shield usable by a ranger) that are obviously not 'for' a certain class, the most appropriate classes that would most practically use the item will be the ones allowed to claim it.  after which classes are allowed to claim an item is confirmed, those present who wish to claim it will send a tell, or say out loud in the raid channel that they wish to claim the item.  the person with the highest points wins, if there is a tie, it is randomed between the players that are tied.  no points are lost for loosing a random ;) only for looting an item.<br>
<br>
4)as far as recruiting scarabs to do your dirty work :)<br>
recruiting scarab's for quest raids/epic raids/etc is very simple: it counts as a regular raid.....yet the drop item is reserved, and will require you to set your points to zero.....in order to make this function unabusable, the following conditions will apply:<br>
a)the amount of groups present, times two, is the minimum amount of points you must have, or be willing to "pay" in order to reserve your item, and call in a quest raid for your item......if there are multiple people who will loot a quest item (eg: the mob drops 2 of them, like VS does, etc) then they will, commutatively, be required to have an amount of points equal or greater to the amount of groups required to do the raid, times two........<br>
example: eejag hit generally requires 1 uber group, or 2 regular groups......since we arent all lvl 60s, it would be most common for it to require 2 groups....so if you want to do this fight, and you are the only monk who is going to get the scale, 2 groups times 2 would be 4 points, thus said, you must have a minimum of 4 points in order to call in this raid.....everyone present will be awarded their regular raid points as if it was a regular 2 group raid........if 2 monks were going to get the scale, then EACH monk must have a minimum of 2 points.....1 monk cant have all 4 points, or 3 points, and the other have 0 or 1......in the case that one monk might pay more then the other, tough luck, thats too bad......in this scenario, the monk(s) looting the scale would be reset to 0, and would recieve no points for the raid (raid points are awarded at the END of a raid after all loot is claimed....keep in mind #1, where it says you must have positive points from a previous raid in order to claim loot)<br>
<br>
5)unclaimed loot will be banked, i suggest we have 3 bank chars all on different accts owned by different ppl, each bank char will specialize in a certain type of loot: 1)gems/quest items 2)your common equipment loot 3)pp, coffins, peris, runes/words/pages, and everything else.......<br>
the gems/quest items char will probably be my druid, which i will be PLing to 24 (is 17 now) so that i can bring him along and camp him outside of any zone we are raiding (or at the zone line) and then come and loot any non claimed ND items, which i can then quite easily MQ later since the druid will of course be able to TP anywhere.  either that or i could use my druid on my 2nd acct who is already 30 and just two-box him (soon as i buy another comp, which should be sometime this month) and that would take care of that :)<br>
i believe runemoon has a mule setup for scarab, and lildariel or whoever else it was that had gotten tons of loot and didnt have room for it......<br>
<br>
these 5 'rules' outline the entire system........everything should be clear, but since im generally not so good at keeping things that way, ask questions for anything that isnt ;)<br>
<br>
unless there is a major disagreement with this rule system, it will soon be put in place........now is your time to speak up or forever hold your peace ;) <p><HR>
